<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 1.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>MCH Knowledge Base/Context</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>1K1.</strong> History and MCH Structure</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Public health is what we do collectively as societies to create conditions in which people can be healthy.<sup>1</sup> This encompasses professionals in a broad range of fields, from first responders and community planners to epidemiologists and infectious-disease specialists. </p>
    <p>MCH focuses on mothers, children, adolescents, and young adults, as well as the families, communities, populations, and community systems of care that support them. This especially applies to individuals who belong to geographically isolated and economically or medically vulnerable populations.</p>
    <p>MCH directs particular attention to six domains. Five of these focus on the populations that comprise maternal and child health. They are:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>All women and in particular women during pregnancy, childbirth, and the postpartum period</li>
      <li>Adolescents (ages 10 to 17) and young adults (ages 18 to 25)</li>
      <li>Babies before, during, and after birth</li>
      <li>Children with special health care needs</li>
      <li>Child health</li>
    </ol>
    <p>A sixth domain, Cross-Cutting and Life Course, addresses program capacity and/or using a life-course perspective as an organizing framework.<br />
       <br />
      The field of MCH is generally considered to have started at the turn of the 20th century. Communicable diseases, an unsafe food supply, and child labor were the chief concerns of the time. Today, advances in health care and technology have brought new and different health challenges to the field.</p>
    <p>Both federal and state funds contribute to MCH-related programs. States and jurisdictions also play an important role in administering these programs. <a href="resource-mch-programs.php" target="_blank">Read more about programs that impact MCH populations (new window)</a>.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-heart-1"></i> <strong>1K2.</strong> Core values and strategic objectives.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The values and objectives at the heart of MCH distinguish it from the broader field of public health.</p>
    <p>MCH puts special focus on the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Prevention: </strong>MCH delivers interventions that successfully address the most pressing public health concerns facing our nation's mothers, children, and families. By preventing death and disability and improving health outcomes over the lifespan, these interventions reduce health care costs and provide long-term economic value to society.</li>
      <li><strong>Individuals and populations:</strong>The health of individuals and populations are linked. MCH places special emphasis on populations that may face challenges in accessing care due to social, physical, genetic, economic, or geographic factors.</li>
      <li><strong>Life course, including key transitions and intergenerational influences on health: </strong>MCH takes a life course approach to health, which means viewing health as an integrated continuum, rather than as disconnected and unrelated stages. The theory behind this posits that there is a "complex interplay" of social and environmental factors mixed with biological, behavioral, and psychological issues that help to define health outcomes across the course of a person's life. Each life stage exerts influence on the next; social, economic, and physical environments also have influence throughout the life course. All these factors impact individual and community health.<sup>3</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Responsiveness to various backgrounds and perspectives:</strong>These fundamental principles create more balanced and inclusive systems that better meet the needs of all families.<sup>4</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Partnerships with individuals with community expertise:</strong>Involving individuals with practical knowledge in program design, implementation, and evaluation allows MCH programs to be more effective and sustainable.<sup>5</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Organizational/interagency partnerships:</strong>These are partnerships formed between agencies and families for the purpose of interdependent problem solving that focuses on improving services to children and their families.<sup>6</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Community-based systems of services: </strong>These are family-centered, coordinated networks of community-based services designed to promote the healthy development and well-being of children and their families.<sup>7</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Improving health outcomes for all groups:</strong> Health variations across different groups can limit a person's ability to be healthy. Working to improve outcomes across all groups should lead to better health for everyone.<sup>8</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Evidence-informed practice:</strong>Using research, contextual, and experiential evidence to drive decision-making at all levels.<sup>9</sup></li>
	  <li><strong>Community circumstances affecting health: </strong>Community circumstances are the conditions in which people are born, grow, live, work, and age. These factors can significantly impact health outcomes, including those related to maternal and child health.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2 level="2"></h2>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>1K3. </strong> Services through MCH programs</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>MCH programs are delivered through a broad system that operates at the federal, state, and local levels. Because each state and the communities within it offer their own combination of programs and initiatives, the array of MCH programs available to a particular individual will differ.</p>
    <p>At the federal level, programs for MCH populations are spread across several departments (Note: This information is meant as a general sketch of the programs available for MCH populations. Please see federal and state websites for more information and updates).</p>
    <h3>Services through the Department of Health and Human Services:</h3>
    <p><strong>Maternal and Child Health (MCH) Services Block Grant program (Title V) </strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Maternal and Child Health Services Block Grant Program, which awards grants to states to fund programs that support maternal and child health.</li>
      <li>Special Projects of Regional and National Significance (SPRANS), a discretionary grant program that supports research and training, genetics services and newborn screening, and treatments for sickle cell disease and hemophilia.</li>
      <li>Community Integrated Service Systems (CISS), a discretionary grant program that seeks to increase local service delivery capacity and foster comprehensive, integrated, community service systems for mothers and children.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Healthy Start Program</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Supports community-driven programs in communities with exceptionally high rates of infant mortality to reduce the prevalence of contributing risk factors. Source: <a href="https://www.hrsa.gov/our-stories/maternal-child/factsheet.html">Factsheet: Maternal and Child Health. (May 2017)</a>. HRSA website. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Medicaid (Title XIX)</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Provides health coverage to eligible low-income children, pregnant women, and people with disabilities. Medicaid is administered by states, according to federal requirements. Amendments to Title XIX include the <strong>Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (ACA) of 2010</strong>, which authorized states to expand Medicaid eligibility to individuals under age 65 in families with incomes below 133 percent of the federal poverty level.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP)</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Gives federal matching funds to states to provide health coverage to children in families with incomes too high to qualify for Medicaid, but who can't afford private coverage.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Community Health Centers</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Provide coordinated and comprehensive primary and preventive services, including oral health and mental health services and opioid addiction treatment, to those facing geographic, linguistic, and socioeconomic barriers to care. Serves one in 12 people overall and one in nine children in the United States.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Family Planning Program (Title X)</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Provides comprehensive and confidential family planning services and preventive health services, including contraception counseling and provision, breast and cervical cancer screenings, testing and treatment for sexually transmitted infections, and pregnancy diagnosis and counseling.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Head Start Program</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Promotes school readiness of children under age five from low-income families through education, health, social and other services.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Welfare or Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF)</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Block grant program for states to design and operate programs that help families in need with food, housing, home energy, child care, job training, and more.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="resource-mch-services.php">Read more about services conducted by other programs</a>.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-town-hall"></i> <strong>1K4. </strong>Key policies that affect MCH populations.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Within the broad system of policies and programs that serve MCH populations, the implications of several policies, laws, and regulations are key:</p>
    <p><strong>Title V MCH Services Block Grant (Title V)</strong>. The MCH Block Grant, authorized by Title V of the Social Security Act, is the only federal program of its kind devoted solely to improving the health of all women and children and is guided by the principles of evidence, flexibility, and results. In FY2017, the Maternal and Child Health Block Grant Program served nearly 99 percent of all infants in the United States.</p>
    <p><strong>Title X (Family Planning Program)</strong>. A network of public and private nonprofit health and community service agencies provides family planning and related preventive health services.</p>
    <p><strong>Title XIX (Medicaid)</strong>. Medicaid is a joint state-federal program. Its purpose is to provide health care to individuals who have low incomes, including persons who are blind or disabled. States, territories, and the District of Columbia must meet certain requirements to receive matching funds from the federal government to participate. The match rate is based on the poverty level within the state.</p>
    <p><strong>IDEA</strong>. The Individuals with Disabilities Education Act establishes a legal, enforceable right to a free, appropriate education, including children and youth with special health care needs.</p>
    <p><strong>WIC</strong>. Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women, Infants, and Children </p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-check-square-o"></i> <strong>1K5. </strong>Underlying principles of public health data collection.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The methods used to collect health-related data include:<sup>13</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Environmental monitoring</li>
      <li>Surveys</li>
      <li>Notifications</li>
      <li>Registries</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Information may be collected from a sample of a population or the entire population. If you are collecting information from a sample of the population, you should take steps to ensure that the samples are randomized. The duration of the time period in which information is collected can vary, from occurring within a limited time to being continuous.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Strengths of Data. </strong>Population data can provide insights into a number of issues:<sup>14,15</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Detect a virus outbreak</li>
      <li>Flag increasing rates of chronic diseases</li>
      <li>Identify drug safety issues and rare side effects</li>
      <li>Track consumer behavior in the health care system</li>
      <li>Can be used to develop interventions or treatments</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Limitations of Data.</strong> When setting up a data collection initiative, carefully consider objectives and thoroughly understand the limitations of each data collection method.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>The completeness of information on diseases and conditions can be highly variable. Reporting on infectious diseases and conditions is likely incomplete, and the degree of completeness might vary depending on the infectious disease or condition and reporting method.<sup>16</sup> There is usually a lag time between when the data was collected and when it was compiled into a database for research use.<sup>17</sup> The degree of completeness of data reporting may be influenced by:<sup>16</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The diagnostic facilities available</li>
      <li>Control measures in effect</li>
      <li>Public awareness of a specific infectious disease or condition</li>
      <li>The resources and priorities of state and local officials responsible for public health surveillance and for controlling infectious diseases and conditions </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Changes in reporting may occur that are independent of the actual incidence of infectious disease or condition. These may be:<sup>16</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Changes in methods for public health surveillance</li>
      <li>Introduction of new diagnostic tests</li>
      <li>Discovery of new infectious disease or condition entities</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Reporting may not include information on race, ethnicity and language, which can be useful during data analysis. These characteristics can be risk markers for certain infectious diseases or conditions that are tracked nationally.<sup>16</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Bias in Data Reporting. </strong>Bias is the tendency of a measurement process to over- or underestimate the value of a measurable characteristic of a population.<sup>18</sup> Common sources of bias in population statistics are:<sup>19</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Selection bias: when the study population does not represent the target population</li>
      <li>Information bias: occurs during data collection</li>
      <li>Confounding: when experimental controls do not allow the experimenter to reasonably eliminate plausible alternative explanations for an observed relationship between independent and dependent variables</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Utility of Data. </strong>National surveillance data is useful for analyzing infectious disease or condition trends and determining relative infectious disease or condition numbers.<sup>16</sup> Population health data can be used to track and develop treatments for widespread health problems such as diabetes and heart disease. It also can be used to design and implement community-wide health initiatives to promote good health practices and discourage negative behaviors.<sup>20</sup></p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-building"></i> <strong>1K6. </strong>Role of government in ensuring  healthcare for all groups.</button>
  <div class="panel">
   
    <p><strong>Balanced Healthcare in the United States</strong></p>
    <p>Balanced healthcare is health care of equal quality for everyone, regardless of race, age, gender, ethnicity, income, geographic location, disability, or any other characteristic. Research indicates that while health care quality has improved overall in recent years, significant differences remain in quality and outcomes by income, race and ethnicity.<sup>21</sup></p>
    <p>Balanced health care can be affected by factors including:<sup>21</sup></p>
    <ul type="disc">
      <li>Affordability</li>
      <li>Access</li>
      <li>Socioeconomic status</li>
      <li> Living conditions&nbsp;</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Government&rsquo;s Role in Ensuring Balanced Healthcare </strong></p>
    <p>Government, whether federal, state, or local, can make health care more balanced by addressing challenges in several domains:<sup>22</sup></p>
    <ul type="disc">
      <li>Access to health care</li>
      <li>Health care quality</li>
      <li>Patient education and empowerment</li>
      <li>Health care infrastructure</li>
      <li>Health care policy and program administration</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Actions that federal, state and local government can take to make health care balanced include:<sup>22</sup> </p>
    <ul type="disc">
      <li>Eliminating health care differences based on race, ethnicity, primary language and income&nbsp;</li>
      <li>Improving the  linguistic competency of both providers and health care systems</li>
      <li>Promoting different backgrounds among health professionals&nbsp;</li>
      <li>Increasing the incentives for health care professionals to practice in underserved      communities</li>
      <li>Putting measures in place to ensure that patients receive quality care regardless of their insurance.</li>
      <li>Ensuring that all women, children, youth, families, and children and youth with special health care needs have a medical home by expanding and promoting      Community Health Centers and other publicly supported health care institutions</li>
      <li>Improving and streamlining enrollment procedures for public health insurance programs</li>
      <li>Making health care affordable through lower out-of-pocket costs, public subsidies to buy health care coverage, sliding scales for premiums and  limits on co-payments for those at the lowest income levels</li>
      <li>Collecting quality-of-care data, stratified by race, ethnicity, primary language and other characteristics of underserved communities to use to incentivize      providers who engage in quality-improvement programs targeting demonstrated health care differences and educating patients</li>
      <li>Supporting and expanding community health worker programs that bridge  trust gaps between providers and underserved communities</li>
      <li>Developing and funding patient education, the training and use of community health workers and prevention programs</li>
      <li>Reducing the financial vulnerability of safety-net hospitals, community health centers, and health care institutions serving poor and minority communities and instituting measures to ensure that financial support is used for its intended purpose</li>
      <li>Using community health planning to better align community needs and health care resources</li>
      <li>At the federal level, supporting health outcomes research, emphasizing social and community research, community-based participatory research and research translation</li></ul></div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-torsos-all-female"></i> <strong>1K7. </strong>Population- and individual-focused program synergy.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Programs focused on populations work to &ldquo;manage&rdquo; health for a group of individuals who usually have been defined by an attribute, such as a predisposition to a disease or disorder. They seek to prevent the onset of a health issue by tracking one or more health indicators.<sup>23</sup></p>
    <p>Programs that focus on communities promote health within a geographically defined group. These programs tend to be multisector and multidisciplinary collaborative enterprises that often originate within the community itself.<sup>23</sup> </p>
    <p>Though population-based programs and community-based programs differ in their approach, they share a focus on enhancing health at an individual level within a defined group.&nbsp;</p>
    <p>Individual health, however, arises from a constellation of factors. As conceptualized by the ecological model of health, linkages and relationships among multiple factors (or determinants) affect health.<sup>24</sup></p>
    <p>These factors are numerous, but generally fall into these categories:<sup>24</sup></p>
    <ul type="disc">
      <li>Individual factors (genetics, individual behaviors)</li>
      <li>Interpersonal factors (social support, family characteristics)</li>
      <li>Institutional and community environments (work sites, service systems, schools, transportation)</li>
      <li>Social, economic and political influences (laws, regulations, racism, discrimination)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Individual health outcomes must be evaluated in the context in which they were created. This context will naturally include communities and populations to which individuals belong.</p>
    <p>Programs intended to affect people from an individual health service delivery perspective must consider the effects of programs targeting the populations and communities those individuals belong to. Similarly, the community and population-based programs must factor in the effects of individual health service delivery programs. The potential for considerable synergy exists among such programs, with the end result that individuals receive timely and appropriate interventions. But absent carefully planning, there also exists the potential for duplicative and unnecessary services to be provided.<sup>25</sup></p>
  </div>
	
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-torsos-all-female"></i> <strong>1K8. </strong>How community generated evidence can complement other evidence forms.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Community-generated evidence (CGE) refers to data collected by community members themselves, often through participatory methods such as surveys, interviews, or observations. This approach offers a unique perspective that can complement traditional research methods in addressing MCH challenges.</p>

	<p>Key Benefits of CGE in MCH</p>
      <ul><li>Contextual relevance: CGE is rooted in the lived experiences of community members, providing insights into local issues,  norms, and barriers to accessing health care.</li>
      <li>Accessibility: Data can be collected at a lower cost and with less complexity than traditional research, making it suitable for resource-limited settings.</li>
      <li>Empowerment: Involving communities in data collection can enhance their sense of agency and ownership over their health issues.</li>
      <li>Bridging the gap: CGE can help bridge the gap between research and practice by providing actionable insights that are relevant to local decision-makers.</li></ul>
 
	  <p>Complementing Traditional Research</p>
<p>While CGE offers valuable insights, it is essential to combine it with traditional research methods for a comprehensive understanding of MCH issues. For example:</p>
  <ul><li>Triangulation: Using multiple data sources can strengthen the validity of findings.</li>
  <li>Data validation: Community-generated data can be used to validate or refine the results of quantitative research.</li>
  <li>Identifying gaps: CGE can help identify issues that may be overlooked by traditional research.</li></ul>
 
<p>Examples of CGE in MCH</p>
    <ul><li>Community health workers can collect data on maternal and child health indicators, such as immunization rates and maternal mortality.</li>
    <li>Community mapping can identify geographic differences in access to health care services.</li>
    <li>Focus groups with community members can reveal their perceptions of health issues and their experiences with health care providers.</li></ul>
 
<p>Challenges and Considerations</p>
    <ul><li>Ensuring the accuracy and reliability of community-generated data requires careful training and supervision of data collectors.</li>
    <li>Ethical considerations, particularly protecting the privacy and confidentiality of participants, is crucial.</li>
    <li>Integration of community-generated evidence into decision-making processes can be challenging, especially in settings where traditional evidence is prioritized.</li></ul>

  </div>
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will:</em></p>
