    <p>View a <a href="https://mchb.tvisdata.hrsa.gov/Home/StateApplicationOrAnnualReport">State Snapshot</a> for each of the 59 states and jurisdictions based on their Title V MCH Block Grant Application/Annual Report.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cog"></i> <strong>1S2. </strong>Describe systems approach.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>A systems approach is &ldquo;a paradigm or perspective that considers connections among different components, plans for the implications of their interaction, and requires transdisciplinary thinking as well as active engagement of those who have a stake in the outcome to govern the course of change.&rdquo;<sup>26</sup> </p>
    <p>It&rsquo;s valuable to be able to view individuals and the health of those individuals as being embedded within systems of structured relationships. There are a number of methods that can be used to visualize how these systems are organized, how they behave over time, and how they can best be controlled.<sup>26</sup> </p>
    <p>Here are a few: </p>
    <p>The <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/violence-prevention/about/index.html">Social-Ecological Model</a> envisions an individual as a circle within a system represented by a series of progressively larger circles that represent spheres of interpersonal influences, community influences, institutional influences, and the influences of local, state andfederal policies and laws to regulate or support healthy actions.</p>
    <p>The <a href="http://www.amchp.org/AboutTitleV/Documents/MCH_Pyramid_Purple.pdf">MCH Pyramid of Health Services</a> envisions a system of services as layers creating a pyramid shape. The base layer is infrastructure-building services, population based and enabling services moving upward, and direct-care services to the individual at the top. The smallest portion of the pyramid represents these direct-care services because these are intended to fill gaps in the services provided to individuals via the previous layers.</p>
    <p>The <a href="https://youtu.be/3OBFYIXmAwQ">Life-Course Model</a> places the various systems that affect children in a temporal context. MCH populations are constantly growing, experiencing different life events, and changing over time. As a result, they will engage with different systems at different points in time.</p>
    <p>Examining an issue or population from a systems perspective allows:<sup>27</sup> </p>
    <ol>
      <li>The appropriate level of intervention to be selected</li>
      <li>Potential partners to be identified and partnerships to be cultivated</li>
      <li>Opportunities to be identified</li>
      <li>Anticipation of unintended consequences</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>1S3. </strong>Use data to identify issues.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Data is essential to identifying issues relevant to MCH populations and informing a systems approach to addressing them.<sup>27</sup> </p>
    <p>Data can be quantitative (measurable) or qualitative (descriptive).</p>
    <p>Data gathered to answer a research question is called <strong>primary data</strong>. </p>
    <p><strong>Secondary data</strong> are collected by another entity or for another purpose. Using secondary data has advantages and disadvantages. <a href="https://www.nihlibrary.nih.gov/resources/subject-guides/health-data-resources/common-data-types-public-health-research">Read more about primary and secondary data</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>Indicators </strong>are secondary data that have been analyzed and can be used to compare rates or trends of priority community health outcomes and determinants.</p>
    <p>Data and indicator analyses provide descriptive information on demographic and socioeconomic characteristics of population groups. They can be used to monitor progress and determine whether actions have the desired effect. They also characterize important parts of health status and health determinants, such as behavior, social and physical environments, and health care use.<sup>28</sup> </p>
    <p>Health assessment indicators should be:<sup>28</sup> </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Methodologically sound (valid, reliable, and collected over time)</li>
      <li>Feasible (available or collectable)</li>
      <li>Meaningful (relevant, actionable, and ideally, linked to evidence-based interventions)</li>
      <li>Important (linked to significant disease burden or disparity in the target community)</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Jurisdictions should consider using data and indicators for the smallest geographic locations possible (e.g., county-, census block-, or ZIP code-level data), to enhance the identification of local assets and gaps.<sup>28</sup> </p>
    <p><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/public-health-gateway/php/public-health-strategy/public-health-strategies-for-community-health-assessment-data-benchmarks.html?CDC_AAref_Val=https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/cha/data.html">View sources of community-level indicators compiled by the CDC</a>. </p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-medkit"></i> <strong>1S4. </strong>Address health needs within MCH populations.</button>
  <div class="panel">
	<p>Community circumstances affecting health are the everyday conditions that affect people's health and well-being. They are all the non-medical things that can make it easier or harder for people to be healthy. These aren't medical factors, but rather the circumstances of our daily lives.</p> 
	  <p>The most common community factors affecting health are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Income and economic stability</li>
        <li>Education access and quality</li>
        <li>Health care access and quality</li>
        <li>Neighborhood and built environment</li>
        <li>Social and community context</li>
        <li>Employment and working conditions</li>
        <li>Food security and nutrition</li>
        <li>Housing stability and quality</li>
        <li>Transportation access</li>
        <li>Environmental conditions (e.g., air and water quality)</li>
        <li>Background and community characteristics</li>
        <li>Gender identity and sexual orientation</li>
        <li>Social support networks</li>
        <li>Childhood experiences and development</li>
        <li>Literacy and language proficiency</li>
      </ul>
       <p>These factors often interact with each other and can have cumulative effects on health outcomes.</p>
       <p>Balanced health opportunities means that all mothers, children and families should have a fair and just opportunity to achieve optimal health outcomes, regardless of their social, economic or demographic circumstances. It goes beyond the concept of equality, which would mean providing the same resources to everyone. Instead, it recognizes that different individuals and communities may need different levels of support and resources to reach the same level of health and well-being.</p> 
	
	<p>Achieving balanced health opportunities requires a multifaceted approach that addresses community circumstances affecting health, which significantly impact maternal and child health outcomes. Activities that address this include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Implementing targeted interventions to support populations with specific needs</li>
      <li>Improving responsiveness to various backgrounds in health care delivery</li>
      <li>Advocating for policies that promote balanced opportunities</li>
      <li>Ensuring that resources are allocated based on need rather than equally distributed</li>
    </ul>
        <p>Ultimately, the goal is to create a system where every mother and child has the opportunity to reach their full health potential, unhindered by social or economic factors.</p>
<p>Health variations generally refer to differences in health status or health outcomes when comparing groups within a subpopulation or the population overall. Populations that may experience different health outcomes include various racial and ethnic groups, as well as people with limited English proficiency (LEP).<sup>24</sup> </p>
    <p>Examples of variations within MCH populations include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Black infants have higher mortality rates (11.1 deaths per 1,000 live births) compared to non-Hispanic white infants (4 deaths per 1,000 live births)</li>
      <li>Black infants are more likely to have low birthweight than white infants<sup>30</sup> </li>
      <li>Quality of care can vary between communities, even when accounting for healthcare insurance coverage and income<sup>31</sup> </li>
      <li>Pregnant women whose first language is not English may have different access to health needs, such as adequate prenatal care services<sup>32</sup></li>
      <li>Maternal mortality rates show significant variations across different groups.<sup>33,34</sup></li>
      <li>Addressing these outcome variations requires leadership at national, state, and community levels. The multiple and complex web of factors causing health variations can be fully addressed only by engaging many partners in fields that influence health such as housing, transportation, education and business. There must be coordination and alignment among federal departments and nonfederal organizations, the implementation of effective policies and programs, and mechanisms to ensure accountability.<sup>35</sup></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-checklist"></i> <strong>1S5. </strong>Evaluate evidence-based programs and policies.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>As a starting point in the process of selecting an evidence-based program (EBP) that will actually translate into concrete practice, MCH professionals need to map out the intervention characteristics they would like to implement. Identify target population, intervention target, baseline level of existing risk factors and problems, and who will deliver the intervention and for how long. </p>
    <p>There are many considerations for MCH professionals to weigh in choosing among possible EBPs, including:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The EBP&rsquo;s evidence base</li>
      <li>Population strengths and needs</li>
      <li>Intervention features, materials, and implementation supports</li>
      <li>Stakeholder values</li>
      <li>Existing practices and organizational support</li>
      <li>Current workforce capacity</li>
      <li>Cost</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comments-1"></i> <strong>1S6. </strong>Partner with family/community organizations</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The Community Health Assessment aNd Group Evaluation (CHANGE) tool from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention enables local stakeholders and community team members to survey and identify community strengths and areas for improvement regarding current policy, systems and environmental change strategies. Guidance from the tool offers insight into the value of partnering with family- and community-led organizations, and can be applied to people with lived experience.</p>
    <p>Action Step 1 of the tool is to assemble a community team:<sup>36</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Representation from various sectors is key to successful teamwork, enables easy and accurate data-collection, and enables data assessment. </li>
      <li>All members of the community team should play an active role, from recommending sites within the sectors to identifying the appropriate data-collection method. This process also ensures that the community team has  access to and informed knowledge of the process. </li>
      <li>Consider the makeup of the community team (10-12 individuals maximum is desirable to ensure the size is manageable and to account for attrition of members). </li>
      <li>Include key decision-makers to  the team and utilize the skill sets of all involved.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="https://usphsicon.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/cdc_changeactionguide.pdf">Read a document outlining the full CHANGE tool</a>.</p>
    <p>Partnerships are stronger if they include people from multiple sectors <em>and </em>people most affected by the problem. Consider the following questions about your team:<sup>37</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does your team reflect the demographic make-up of your community?</li>
      <li>Does it work to engage community members in a meaningful way?</li>
      <li>Does it leverage a variety set of skills and expertise? </li>
      <li>Does it engage new groups, especially those interested in policy or systems change? </li>
    </ul>
    <p>See more information about how to <a href="https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-improve-health/action-center/work-together">Recruit  Stakeholders From Multiple Sectors</a></p>
  </div>
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>1S7. </strong>Demonstrate a systems approach.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The work that goes on within MCH usually takes place within a larger context. It is important to be able to look at a problem or situation and identify the various systems involved, how they affect what is going on, and how MCH professionals can work at a systems level to create a positive outcome.<sup>27</sup></p>
    <p>MCH professionals need to be able to work at every level of the system they&rsquo;ve defined for a problem or goal:<sup>27</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>With individual women and their families</li>
      <li>Within communities, work environments, home environments</li>
      <li>Within the health care delivery and financing systems</li>
      <li>Within the social structure and policy environment</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Let&rsquo;s apply a systems approach to the goal of helping women have healthy pregnancy outcomes.</p>
    <p>To achieve this goal, women will need to access a range of systems. </p>
    <p>Women will need access to preconception health care to receive:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Well-woman care</li>
      <li>Family planning services</li>
      <li>Pregnancy planning services</li>
    </ul>
    <p>From a systems perspective, to receive these services, women will need:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Health insurance coverage for preconception care</li>
      <li>Access to providers who offer these services</li>
      <li>Time off from work, child care, transportation, and possibly translation services</li>
      <li>Family and partner support</li>
      <li>An understanding of why preconception care is important</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Once they are pregnant, women will need: </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Access to prenatal care </li>
      <li>A supportive environment</li>
    </ul>
    <p>From a systems perspective, delivering these services will require:<br />
      At the macro level:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Insurance coverage for the service</li>
      <li>Provider availability and knowledge</li>
      <li>Work leave, child care, transportation, translation</li>
      <li>Options for delivery</li>
    </ul>
    <p>At the micro (personal) level:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Supportive partner, family</li>
      <li>Limited stress/fear no violence</li>
      <li>Support for lifestyle changes</li>
    </ul>
    <p>At the time of delivery, women will need:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Access to the hospital of their choice</li>
      <li>A care plan</li>
      <li>Medical care that matches their level of risk</li>
    </ul>
    <p>From a systems perspective, delivering these services will require:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Insurance coverage for delivery</li>
      <li>Provider involvement and care coordination</li>
      <li>Hospitals able to provide appropriate medical interventions should they be required</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Post-delivery, women will need </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Breastfeeding support </li>
      <li>A safe ride home to a safe environment</li>
      <li>A safe sleep environment for the baby/babies</li>
    </ul>
    <p>From a systems perspective, delivering these services will require:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Lactation services</li>
      <li>Safe-sleep education</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Each system involved in this example focuses on one service or set of services. MCH professionals are responsible for coordinating all of the systems toward a bigger-picture solution.<sup>27</sup> </p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-star"></i> <strong>1S8. </strong>Assess effectiveness of existing programs.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Conduct a <strong>formative evaluation</strong> prior to starting program or program activity to find out if it is feasible, appropriate, and acceptable before it is fully implemented for the target population. </p>
    <p>Tracking progress on selected outcomes is important to determine how a program is working. This may mean monitoring large-scale outcomes at the population scale, such as incidence of a disease or improvement of a condition, or individual-level factors, such as behavior change. </p>
    <p>Define what you will track and the sources of data you&rsquo;ll use, as well as how frequently you&rsquo;ll gather data. If collecting data requires administering assessments or surveys to individuals, plan for when and how that will take place.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Impact evaluation</strong> is used to assess the extent to which program objectives are being met, and may reflect changes in knowledge, attitudes, behavior, or other intermediate outcomes.</li>
      <li><strong>Outcome/effectiveness evaluation</strong> measures program effects in the target population by assessing the progress in the outcomes or outcome objectives that the program is to achieve. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Typically, measures are taken before an intervention is implemented and when the intervention is over to provide an indicator of change. However, collecting data at multiple time points during the intervention can yield an early indication of the intervention&rsquo;s impact and provide a chance to troubleshoot problems. </p>
    <p>The extent to which an intervention was implemented as it was intended is known as <strong>fidelity</strong>. Changing an intervention reduces the fidelity. Evidence suggests that lower fidelity negatively affects an intervention&rsquo;s effectiveness.</p>
    <p>Use <strong>process evaluation</strong> to assess whether a program is being implemented as intended. Plan for this assessment by identifying the methods you will use to measure fidelity, how often you&rsquo;ll measure, and what represents an appropriate level of fidelity. Some programs may have already established fidelity measures or published recommendations for assessing and benchmarking fidelity. For programs that don&rsquo;t offer guidance on fidelity monitoring, identify how similar programs recommend measuring fidelity.</p>
    
  </div>

  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-star"></i> <strong>1S9. </strong>Ensure balanced opportunities and responsiveness to various backgrounds at forefront</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Making balanced health opportunities and responsiveness to various backgrounds central to MCH work requires intentional focus throughout all activities. This involves embedding these considerations into program design, implementation, and evaluation processes.</p>
    <p>At the program level, this means involving stakeholders from various backgrounds and individuals with practical knowledge in planning, conducting linguistic needs assessments, and designing programs that address community circumstances affecting health. Service delivery should include linguistically appropriate services, staff training in responsiveness to various backgrounds, and creating welcoming environments that reflect the communities served.</p>
    <p>Data collection and evaluation must include metrics categorized by relevant factors to identify and track outcome variations. Organizations should develop leadership that reflects various backgrounds, create policies promoting balanced opportunities, and build meaningful partnerships with community-based organizations.</p>
    <p>Regular assessment of organizational responsiveness to various populations and willingness to make changes based on community input helps ensure that balanced opportunities and responsiveness to various backgrounds remain at the forefront of MCH work.</p>
    
  </div>
  
