<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Linking to the Peer-Reviewed Literature</h3>
  <p>In this section, we link the competency  to seminal  peer-reviewed articles. This  aligns the competency to the established and emerging evidence base and with expertise from leaders in the field. You can access these resources and read at your own pace for a deeper understanding of the competency. As you read the articles, reflect on how the science has informed practice. <em>Tip: you can read the abstract now and access the full article for future reading.</em></p>
  <p><strong>Articles to Explore:</strong></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-file-text-o"></i> <strong>Our Legacy for Leadership in MCH. </strong>Alexander, GR.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <h4><a href="../documents/Alexander2003_Article_OurLegacyForLeadershipInMCH.pdf">Our Legacy for Leadership in MCH</a></h4>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Citation.</strong> Alexander, GR. Our Legacy for Leadership in MCH. <em>Matern Child Health J</em> <strong>7, </strong>145–150 (2003). https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1025153819412. </p>
      <p><strong>Abstract.</strong> The history of Maternal and Child Health (MCH) in the United States provides some important lessons for us today. Emerging from the child labor abolition and progressive reform movements of the late 1800s, the basis of MCH in the United States can be traced to fundamental concerns regarding how our society should protect children from a host of threats, including abuse, the adverse practices of childhood labor, disease, and the ill effects of unclean milk and water, poor sanitation, and an unsafe environment. These and additional concerns about how to assure that children and families have access to adequate healthcare and to health and social systems that understand the special developmental needs of children persist to this day. A review of the history of MCH fosters an appreciation of the many accomplishments made by early MCH leaders during some very difficult times in this country. Today, with the advent of war and an unclear economic forecast, to say nothing of continuing health care reforms and the reinvention of the roles and purposes of public health, it may offer modest comfort to know that our predecessors faced grim circumstances too and prevailed. As MCH continues to evolve in response to the major social events of the times, there is an ongoing need to revisit and reflect upon the role and purpose of MCH in the society. Our inherited legacy of leadership in MCH both inspires and challenges us as we strive to responsibly advocate, align constituencies, build and use data capacities for need assessment and evaluation, question our premises, identify and courageously confront pressing health and social issues, and continue our efforts to formulate and articulate a vision for the future of MCH. </p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-file-text-o"></i> <strong>Leading Maternal and Child Health (MCH): Past, Present and Future. </strong>Petersen, DJ.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <h4><a href="../documents/Petersen2015_Article_LeadingMaternalAndChildHealthM.pdf">Leading Maternal and Child Health (MCH): Past, Present and Future</a></h4>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Citation.</strong> Petersen DJ. Leading maternal and child health (MCH): past, present and future. Matern Child Health J. 2015 Feb;19(2):244-6. doi: 10.1007/s10995-014-1565-1. PMID: 25001501.</p>
      <p><strong>Abstract.</strong> The field of maternal and child health (MCH) was borne out of leadership, leadership manifested in the foresight of a group of women who applied passion, skill and evidence to create a unifying vision for the nation&rsquo;s children and families and the means for continuous investment in this vision. From these prescient social reformers to those who nurtured the field through periods of opportunity and strife, the ability of leaders to anticipate, to champion, to negotiate and to advocate or exhort has shaped what may be the most important sustained public health effort in our nation&rsquo;s history. Two perspectives must be made clear: first, MCH as a collective must don the mantle of leadership in recognition of the enormous responsibility it holds as a statutorily mandated program and a social movement to protect and promote the health and economic vitality of the nation. The second perspective posits that each of us in the collective must cultivate our own leadership skills in order to create and manage the change that is necessary within whatever organizational, institutional or community setting we find ourselves. </p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-file-text-o"></i> <strong>Rethinking MCH: The Life Course Model as an Organizing Framework. </strong>Fine A, Kotelchuck M.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <h4><a href="https://mchnutritionpartners.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Kotelchuck-paper_Rethinking-MCH.pdf">Rethinking MCH: The Life Course Model as an Organizing Framework Concept Paper</a></h4>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Citation. </strong>Fine A, Kotelchuck M. Rethinking MCH: The Life Course Model as an Organizing Framework Concept Paper. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Health Resources and Services Administration, Maternal and Child Health Bureau. 2010.</p>
      <p><strong>Abstract.</strong> This concept paper was commissioned by MCHB to provide a mutual understanding about MCH life course from which the broad MCH community can begin to shape its public health approaches for the 21st century. The paper clarifies and synthesizes the best thinking on MCH life course and outlines how the theory might be used to frame MCHB&rsquo;s upcoming strategic planning process. The paper provides a series of examples for how a life course perspective might be incorporated into MCH research, programs, policies and partnerships to optimize health outcomes  across the population. These ideas are offered as a starting point to jump-start a national dialogue. It is hoped that the suggestions in the paper will trigger a rich and fruitful interchange that will help MCHB and its many partners move from life course theory into life course practice.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</div>
<h2><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> 1.2.2 PRACTICE</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. A Crosswalk of Trainings</h3>
  <p>In this section, we present additional trainings that directly support the knowledge and skill areas described above and specific skills that support related concepts/competencies. <em>Tip: you can  explore and bookmark these  trainings as good references to review outside the curriculum</em></p>
  <p><strong>Trainings to Explore:</strong></p>
  <button class="accordion"> <strong><i class="mch-tag-stroke"></i> MCH Leadership Competency 1: MCH Knowledge Base/Context. </strong>Additional Trainings.</button>
  <div class="panel">
